# migrated from tests/cases/gen_interp.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated)
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test gen_interp]
# gen42: interpolation over hard backoff. gen38 backed off hard -- ANY trigram
# continuation, even seen once, overrode the bigram model (Decision
# D-2026-06-15k). gen42 instead SCORES each candidate w by
# W2*cont2(p2,p1,w) + W1*cont(p1,w) (W2=3, W1=1): the longer context informs
# the choice without dictating it. Held-out tokens; no randomness.
#
# Teach a strong bigram y->a (five times, no trigram context).
> learn sequence: y a
< Learned 1 transition(s).
> learn sequence: y a
< Learned 1 transition(s).
> learn sequence: y a
< Learned 1 transition(s).
> learn sequence: y a
< Learned 1 transition(s).
> learn sequence: y a
< Learned 1 transition(s).
# Now teach a single trigram x y b: it makes cont2(x,y,b)=1, cont(y,b)=1.
> learn sequence: x y b
< Learned 2 transition(s).
# Hard backoff (gen38) would emit "x y b" -- the lone trigram overriding the
# strong bigram. Interpolation keeps "a": score(a)=0+5 beats score(b)=3+1.
> say x
< x y a
# But trigram context still wins when its evidence is real: teach x y b twice
# more (cont2(x,y,b)=3) -> score(b)=9+3=12 beats score(a)=0+5=5. Choice flips.
> learn sequence: x y b
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> learn sequence: x y b
< Learned 2 transition(s).
> say x
< x y b

